title: For Sale:  Marlin XL7 .223 Remington
location: Near Idaho Falls Temple, Idaho Falls, Idaho
postcontent:
This is one of my favorite guns. I bought it last year in the beginning of November, they usually go for around 360. The rifle has had about 500 rounds through it, it shoots pretty good. To break it in and for plinking I’ve been shooting Wolf Gold, which groups pretty good for cheap ammo at about 1.5 inches. HPR ammo with 55 gr. VMAX bullets shoots at about 1 inch. 24 grains of IMR 4198 with a 55 gr Sierra varminter bullet was really good; I shot one group at about a half inch but honestly I’ve never been able to replicate that, but normally its under an inch. So the gun shoots really well. I put a Nikon 3-9×40 scope with the BDC reticle, the scope came off of a Savage Trophy Hunter XP.  The scope with the rings is worth about 150.
I glass bedded the action and the fore end of the stock to stiffen it up. It made it a little heavier but it shoots better. The X7 or XL7 is is a good gun, they basically just combined all the popular parts from all the guns into this one (Rem 700 safety, Win 70 bases and bold release, Savage trigger and barrel nut). I’m not set on the price so make me an offer. REDACTED.
Here are a couple review that were done about this gun:
http://www.americanrifleman.org/articles/2013/12/11/the-marlin-x7/
http://www.shootingtimes.com/long-guns/longgun_reviews_marlin_corners_the_market_102910/

title: For Sale/Trade:  Suzuki gsxr 750 project/parts bike
postcontent:
I have a 92 gsxr 750 project that I had traded for before I realized sport bikes are too complex for me and being a 21y/o male (statistically most likely to buy and wreck these bikes) not a good idea insurance wise.
The bike is pretty much stripped at the moment. It's a Suzuki gsxr 750 frame and engine. Engine had compression test done prior to me trading for it and compression is good. Has a hayabusa swingarm, suspension and rear rim/tire on it. Rear tire is worn but front still has life to it. I have the wiring harness, a spare harness for backup parts, a coil kit (aftermarket, unused with plenty length to cut to size) 
Carb rack (minus the screws for the float bowls) and pod filters, 4-2-1 ceramic coated header, and an aluminum plate machined for between the 750 frame and top connection of the busa shock to keep the geometry right.
It has the original sub frame removed and I have the stainless steel tubing in different sizes to make a custom subframe of chosen size and shape as well as the "slugs" to bridge the tubing to the frame.
It is definitely a project so if you are into putting in time and energy for a custom outcome it's a decent start but if you aren't into projects it's probably not what you're looking for.
Has title.
Looking to get 500 obo. Need it gone soon and parts are worth more if you part it out but it's taking up space that I don't have and I need to get rid of it before HOA a-holes make me completely lose my mind.
